1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT PROVIDING FOR AND ENHANCING PATIENT SAFETY IN MEDICAL
3 IMAGING BY ENSURING EDUCATIONALLY PREPARED AND CLINICALLY
4 COMPETENT PERSONS PERFORM AND ADMINISTER MEDICAL IMAGING AND
5 RADIATION THERAPY PROCEDURES.
6 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
7 SECTION 1. Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
8 to read:
9 "Article 44.
10 "Radiologic Technologists, Radiation Therapists, Sonographers.
11 "§ 90-750. Short title; findings.
12 (a) This Article may be cited as the "Patient Safety in Medical Imaging Act."
13 (b) The General Assembly finds and declares that citizens in this State are entitled to the
14 highest quality of care and maximum protection practicable from the harmful effects of
15 improperly performed medical imaging and radiation therapy procedures and that protection and
16 quality can be increased by requiring appropriate education and licensure of persons operating
17 equipment used for medical imaging and radiation therapy procedures. Therefore, it is essential
18 to establish standards of education for these professionals and to provide for appropriate
19 examination and licensure.
20 "§ 90-751. Definitions.
21 The following definitions apply in this Article:
22 (1) Board. – The Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy Board of Examiners.
23 (2) Bone densitometry. – The determination of bone mass by means of the
24 radiation absorption by a skeleton or part of a skeleton.
25 (3) Cardiac electrophysiology specialist. – A person who is registered to perform,
26 under the supervision of a qualified physician, radiographic procedures and
27 studies using external ionizing radiation to produce fluoroscopic images.
28 (4) Cardiovascular invasive specialist. – A person who is registered to perform,
29 under the supervision of a qualified physician, radiographic procedures using
30 external ionizing radiation to produce fluoroscopic images.
31 (5) Certification organization. – A national certification organization that
32 specializes in the certification and registration of medical imaging or radiation
33 therapy technical personnel and is accredited by the National Commission for
34 Certifying Agencies, the American National Standards Institute, or other
35 accreditation organization recognized by the Board.
*H590-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) Computed tomography. – The process of producing sectional and
2 three-dimensional images using external ionizing radiation for diagnostic or
3 therapeutic purposes.
4 (7) Diagnostic medical sonographer. – A person who is licensed under this Article
5 to perform diagnostic medical sonography procedures using high-frequency
6 sound waves with specialized equipment to direct the sound waves into an
7 area of the human body to generate an image for diagnostic purposes or for
8 the purpose of providing guidance during medical interventions.
9 (8) Diagnostic medical sonography. – The use of high-frequency sound waves
10 (ultrasound) with specialized equipment to direct the sound waves into an area
11 of the human body to generate an image for diagnostic or therapeutic
12 purposes.
13 (9) Fluoroscopy. – The continuous exposure of a patient to X rays in real-time
14 imaging of structures inside of the body during real-time procedures.
15 (10) Hybrid imaging. – The combination of imaging technologies that allows
16 information from different modalities to be presented as a single set of images.
17 (11) Ionizing radiation. – As defined by G.S. 104E-5(9).
18 (12) Licensed practitioner. – A person licensed to practice medicine, dentistry,
19 podiatry, nursing, or chiropractic medicine in this State.
20 (13) Limited practice radiographer. – A person who is licensed under this Article
21 to perform, under the supervision of a radiographer or licensed practitioner,
22 radiography or bone densitometry procedures resulting in diagnostic
23 radiographic images of selected specific parts of human anatomy or bone
24 density measurements.
25 (14) Magnetic resonance. – The use of radiofrequencies within a magnetic field for
26 diagnostic, therapeutic, or research purposes.
27 (15) Medical imaging. – Any procedure or article intended for use in the diagnosis
28 or visualization of disease or other medical conditions in human beings,
29 including radiography, nuclear medicine, fluoroscopy, magnetic resonance,
30 sonography, and other procedures using ionizing radiation or nonionizing
31 radiation.
32 (16) Medical imaging professional. – An individual other than a licensed
33 practitioner who has undergone appropriate training and testing by a
34 Board-approved certification organization to be licensed in the individual's
35 practicing modality.
36 (17) Mobile imaging. – Any arrangement in which medical imaging services are
37 transported to various sites. This term does not include movement within a
38 hospital or movement to a site where the equipment will be located
39 permanently.
40 (18) Modality. – Technologies used in the diagnosis or treatment of disease or other
41 medical conditions in human beings, including all of the following:
42 a. Diagnostic medical sonography and its specializations.
43 b. Magnetic resonance.
44 c. Nuclear medicine and its specializations.
45 d. Radiation therapy and its specializations.
46 e. Radiography and its specializations.
47 (19) Nonionizing radiation. – As defined in G.S. 104E-5.
48 (20) Nuclear medicine technologist. – A person who is licensed under this Article
49 to perform nuclear medicine and molecular imaging procedures using sealed
50 and unsealed radiation sources, ionizing and nonionizing radiation, adjunctive
51 medicines, and therapeutic procedures using unsealed radioactive sources.
