1 (21) Public member. – A resident of North Carolina who is not a licensed
2 practitioner, does not perform medical imaging or radiation therapy
3 procedures under this Article, and is not affiliated with any group or
4 profession that provides or regulates health care or that may, in any way,
5 hinder the public member in representing the interest of the public.
6 (22) Radiation therapist. – A person who is licensed under this Article to perform
7 procedures involving the administration of external source ionizing radiation
8 to human beings for therapeutic purposes.
9 (23) Radiographer. – A person who is licensed under this Article to perform a
10 comprehensive set of diagnostic radiographic procedures using external
11 ionizing radiation to produce radiographic, fluoroscopic, or digital images.
12 (24) Radiologist. – A physician licensed under Article 1 of this Chapter who is
13 Board-eligible for certification or who is certified by the American Board of
14 Radiology, the American Osteopathic Board of Radiology, the British Royal
15 College of Radiology, or the Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of
16 Canada.
17 (25) Radiologist assistant. – A licensed radiographer who is additionally licensed
18 under this Article to perform a variety of activities under the supervision of a
19 radiologist in the areas of patient care, patient management, and medical
20 imaging procedures.
21 "§ 90-753. Scope of practice; limitations.
22 (a) The Board shall establish licensure standards for the following radiologic imaging
23 and radiation therapy modalities:
24 (1) Computed tomography.
25 (2) Cardiac invasive specialist.
26 (3) Cardiac electrophysiology specialist.
27 (4) Diagnostic medical sonography.
28 (5) Limited practice radiographer.
29 (6) Magnetic resonance.
30 (7) Nuclear medicine technologist.
31 (8) Radiation therapist.
32 (9) Radiographer.
33 (10) Radiologist assistant.
34 (b) A person licensed in medical imaging or radiation therapy under this Article may use
35 radioactive substances, equipment emitting ionizing radiation or nonionizing radiation for
36 medical imaging, or radiation therapy procedures only by prescription of an individual authorized
37 by the State to prescribe medical imaging or radiation therapy procedures and under the
38 supervision of a licensed practitioner.
39 (c) Individuals licensed as limited practice radiographers shall perform tasks only within
40 the scope of the specific permit issued to them as provided in G.S. 90-756(c)(1) under the
41 supervision of a licensed practitioner or radiographer and shall not perform computed
42 tomography, diagnostic medical sonography, fluoroscopy, mammography, magnetic resonance
43 imaging, radiation therapy, mobile imaging procedures, or imaging procedures using contrast
44 media.
45 (d) Individuals licensed as cardiovascular invasive specialists shall be registered and
46 licensed to perform, under the supervision of a qualified physician, radiographic procedures
47 using external ionizing radiation to produce fluoroscopic images. To qualify for a license under
48 this subsection, an applicant shall meet all of the following requirements:
49 (1) Possess a high school diploma or equivalent.
50 (2) Possess a current certification in advanced cardiac life support.
51 (3) Complete an accredited cardiovascular technology program.
