1 (4) Possess current credentials as a registered cardiovascular invasive specialist
2 offered by Cardiovascular Credentialing International, Cardiac Interventional
3 Radiography, or Cardiovascular Interventional Radiography, as offered by the
4 American Registry Radiologic Technologists or other certification
5 organization as approved by the Board.
6 (e) Individuals licensed as cardiovascular electrophysiology specialists shall be
7 registered and licensed to perform, under the supervision of a qualified physician, radiographic
8 procedures using external ionizing radiation to produce fluoroscopic images. To qualify for a
9 license under this subsection, an applicant shall meet all of the following requirements:
10 (1) Possess a high school diploma or equivalent.
11 (2) Possess a certificate or degree in health science or possess two years of
12 full-time work experience in diagnostic and interventional cardiac
13 electrophysiology.
14 (3) Graduate from an accredited program in electrophysiology.
15 (4) Possess current credentials as a registered cardiovascular electrophysiology
16 specialist offered by Cardiovascular Credentialing International or other
17 certification organization as approved by the Board.
18 (f) Effective January 1, 2026, all individuals licensed to perform medical imaging and
19 radiation therapy who perform computed tomography for diagnostic purposes must be certified
20 in computed tomography by the American Registry of Radiologic Technologists, the Nuclear
21 Medicine Technology Certification Board, or another certification organization recognized by
22 the Board.
23 (g) A person licensed to perform nuclear medicine technology may perform computed
24 tomography for attenuation correction and localization on hybrid imaging equipment.
25 (h) A person licensed to perform radiation therapy may perform computed tomography
26 or other modalities for treatment planning purposes.
27 (i) A person licensed to perform radiography may perform fluoroscopy and bone
28 densitometry.
29 (j) A person licensed as a radiologist assistant shall not interpret images, make diagnoses,
30 or prescribe medications or therapies.
31 "§ 90-754. Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy Board of Examiners.
32 (a) Composition of Board. – The North Carolina Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy
33 Board of Examiners is hereby created. The Board shall consist of a maximum of nine members
34 appointed by the Governor and shall serve at the pleasure of the Governor. The initial Board shall
35 be appointed within 90 days following the effective date of this section. The members of the
36 Board shall include:
37 (1) One licensed nuclear medicine technologist.
38 (2) One licensed practitioner who is a radiologist and supervises medical imaging
39 or radiation therapy professionals.
40 (3) One certified radiological or therapeutic physicist.
41 (4) One licensed radiation therapist.
42 (5) One licensed computed tomography technologist or radiographer.
43 (6) One licensed magnetic resonance imaging technologist or licensed
44 sonographer.
45 (7) One radiologist assistant.
46 (8) One retired medical imaging professional as public member.
47 (9) One licensed radiography educator.
48 (b) Board Member Qualifications for Appointment. – In addition to the requirements of
49 subsection (a) of this section, Board members shall meet the following qualifications:
50 (1) Each Board member shall be a resident of the State of North Carolina.
51 (2) The public member shall be at least 21 years of age.
Page 4 House Bill 590-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Except for the public member and the licensed practitioners, each Board
2 member shall have at least two years of experience performing medical
3 imaging or radiation therapy in the modality for which the Board member is
4 appointed.
5 (c) Terms of Office. – The terms of office shall be three years, except that the terms of
6 the members appointed to the initial Board shall be as follows: three members shall be appointed
7 for a term of one year, three members for a term of two years, and three members for a term of
8 three years. Vacancies shall be filled for an unexpired term only in the manner provided by the
9 original appointment. No member shall be eligible for appointment to serve more than two
10 consecutive terms.
11 (d) Temporary Board Exemption to License Requirements. – A person who performs
12 medical imaging or radiation therapy procedures and is appointed to the initial Board shall not
13 be required to hold a valid license issued by the Board until 12 months after the first issuance of
14 a license by the Board.
15 (e) Compensation and Expenses. – Each member of the Board shall receive per diem and
16 reimbursement for travel and subsistence as provided in G.S. 93B-5.
17 (f) Officers. – The officers of the Board shall be a chair and a vice-chair, and other
18 officers deemed necessary by the Board to carry out the purposes of this Article. All officers shall
19 be elected annually by the Board for one-year terms and shall serve until their successors are
20 elected and qualified.
21 (g) Meetings. – The Board shall hold four meetings each year, once per quarter, to
22 conduct business and to review the standards and rules for improving the administration of
23 medical imaging or radiation therapy procedures. The Board shall establish the procedures for
24 calling, holding, and conducting regular and special meetings. A majority of Board members
25 constitutes a quorum.
26 (h) Meeting Attendance. – A member of the Board who fails to attend three meetings in
27 an 18-month period shall forfeit the member's seat unless the chair, upon written request from
28 the member, finds that the member should be excused from a meeting because of illness or death
29 of a family member.
30 (i) Quorum. – A majority of the voting members of the Board shall constitute a quorum.
31 No action may be taken by the Board except by affirmative vote of the majority of those present
32 and voting.
33 "§ 90-755. Powers of the Board.
34 The Board shall have the following powers and duties:
35 (1) Administer this Article.
36 (2) Issue interpretations of this Article.
37 (3) Adopt rules as may be necessary to carry out the provisions of this Article.
38 (4) Establish the scope of practice for each license or permit type issued by the
39 Board.
40 (5) Employ and fix the compensation of personnel that the Board determines is
41 necessary to carry into effect the provisions of this Article and incur other
42 expenses necessary to effectuate this Article.
43 (6) Examine and determine the qualifications and fitness of applicants for
44 licensure, renewal of licensure, and reciprocal licensure. The Board may, in
45 its discretion, revise the licensing requirements of this Article for areas of
46 North Carolina that the Board deems too remote to contain enough qualified
47 licensees to perform medical imaging or radiation therapy procedures on
48 humans for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes.
49 (7) Set requirements for continuing education as a requirement for license
50 renewal. The Board may review and accept the continuing education and
51 recertification or continuing competency requirements established by a
