4 SECTION 2. Article 44 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes, as enacted by Section
5 1 of this act, is amended by adding new sections to read:
6 "§ 90-752. License required; exemptions.
7 (a) License Required. – Except as provided in this section, only a person currently
8 licensed under this Article may perform or offer to perform radiologic imaging or radiation
9 therapy procedures on humans for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes or otherwise indicate or
10 imply that the person is licensed to perform radiologic imaging or radiation therapy procedures.
11 (b) License Required for Employment. – No person or business entity shall knowingly
12 employ a person who does not hold a license, or is not exempt under this Article, to perform
13 radiologic imaging or radiation therapy procedures on humans for diagnostic or therapeutic
14 purposes.
15 (c) No Limitation or Enlargement of Practice. – Nothing in this Article shall limit or
16 enlarge the practice of a licensed practitioner.
17 (d) Exemptions. – The provisions of this Article shall not apply to the following:
18 (1) A licensed practitioner performing medical imaging procedures or
19 administering radiation therapy.
20 (2) A registered dental hygienist (RDH).
21 (3) A dental assistant I or II who has satisfactorily completed one of the following:
22 a. The North Carolina radiography equivalency examination.
23 b. Dental assisting school through an American Dental
24 Association-accredited program.
25 c. The Dental Assisting National Board examination.
26 d. Classification as a dental assistant II in this State under the laws
27 regulating the practice of dentistry.
28 (4) A resident physician licensed under Article 1 of this Chapter.
29 (5) A student enrolled in and attending a school or college of medicine or medical
30 imaging or radiation therapy who performs medical imaging or radiation
31 therapy procedures on humans while under the supervision of a licensed
32 practitioner, or an individual holding a license under this Article.
33 (6) A person administering radiologic imaging or radiation procedures as an
34 employee of the United States government.
35 (7) A person performing radiologic procedures or therapy on cadavers.
36 (8) A person licensed to perform radiologic imaging or radiation therapy who is
37 performing supervised clinical procedures in preparation for certification in
38 an additional radiologic imaging or radiation therapy modality who has
39 registered with the Board. The Board may grant this exemption for a period
40 not to exceed three years, and this exemption may be renewed by the Board.
41 (9) Chiropractic students as described in G.S. 90-142.1 and diagnostic imaging
42 technicians as described in G.S. 90-143.2.
43 (10) A licensed veterinarian performing medical imaging procedures or
44 administering radiation therapy, or to an individual employed by, or engaged
45 as an independent contractor by, a licensed veterinarian that performs a
46 medical imaging procedure or administers radiation therapy in the ordinary
47 course of their employment or engagement.
48 (11) An individual employed by, or engaged as an independent contractor by, a
49 podiatrist that performs medical imaging procedures in the ordinary course of
50 their employment or engagement.
51 (12) A certified registered nurse anesthetist performing fluoroscopy.
House Bill 590-Third Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (13) A nurse practitioner or physician assistant performing fluoroscopy.
2 "§ 90-763. Violation a misdemeanor; injunctive relief.
3 (a) Any person who violates any provision of this Article shall be guilty of a Class 1
4 misdemeanor. Each act of such unlawful practice shall constitute a distinct and separate offense.
5 (b) The Board may make application to any appropriate court for an order enjoining
6 violations of this Article, and upon a showing by the Board that any person has violated or is
7 about to violate this Article, the court may grant an injunction or restraining order or take other
8 appropriate action."
9 SECTION 3. Notwithstanding the requirements of G.S. 90-754, as enacted by
10 Section 1 of this act, the initial appointees to the Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy Board
11 of Examiners filling the membership positions for licensed radiologist, licensed nuclear medicine
12 technologist, licensed radiation therapist, and licensed sonographer do not have to meet the
13 licensure requirements established in Section 1 of this act, provided that these initial appointees
14 shall apply for and obtain a license from the Board within 90 days after the Board begins issuing
15 licenses.
16 SECTION 4. Persons other than radiologist assistants who have been engaged in the
17 practice of medical imaging and radiation therapy and who do not hold a current registration
18 from a voluntary professional certification organization approved by the Medical Imaging and
19 Radiation Therapy Board of Examiners may continue to practice in the modality of medical
20 imaging or radiation therapy in which they are currently employed provided that they (i) register
21 with the Board on or before October 1, 2026, (ii) do not change the scope of their current
22 employment practice, (iii) complete all continuing education requirements for their area of
23 practice annually as prescribed by the Board, and (iv) practice only under the supervision of a
24 radiologist.
25 SECTION 5. If any provision of this act or its application is held invalid, the
26 invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this act that can be given effect
27 without the invalid provisions or application and, to this end, the provisions of this act are
28 severable.
29 SECTION 6. No later than January 1, 2026, The Medical Imaging and Radiation
30 Therapy Board of Examiners shall adopt rules to implement the provisions of this act.
31 SECTION 7. Section 1 of this act becomes effective July 1, 2025. Section 2 of this
32 act becomes effective January 1, 2026. The remainder of this act is effective when it becomes
33 law.
